WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.440
Okay, so I'd like to begin by taking you back to a time when Obama was first inaugurated,

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:22.440
Edward Snowden had just fled the country, and Shiny was still in its infancy.

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:29.639
The year was 2013, and at the time, folks were absolutely thrilled to be creating reactive

00:00:29.639 --> 00:00:36.439
web applications in R and thrilled that it looked like this.

00:00:36.439 --> 00:00:43.279
Turns out, more than ten years later, you can run that exact same code with the latest

00:00:43.279 --> 00:00:47.400
Shiny and get basically the same result.

00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:51.880
There's not a lot of R packages out there that can claim something like this, that you

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:58.040
can take the same code that you learned and wrote ten years ago and run it today and you

00:00:58.040 --> 00:01:01.799
get the same result.

00:01:01.799 --> 00:01:09.559
But let me step back and ask, is this a feature, or is it a bug?

00:01:09.559 --> 00:01:16.559
It's maybe somewhere in between in the sense that this is really great if you value reproducibility

00:01:16.559 --> 00:01:21.480
and stability, that you can have a certain level of confidence that the code that you're

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:26.639
writing today or the code you wrote ten years ago, we're going to put in a lot of effort

00:01:26.760 --> 00:01:30.720
to make sure that that code is going to work in the future, that you can deploy the same

00:01:30.720 --> 00:01:35.680
application and count on that still working.

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:41.919
But on the other hand, for someone just getting started with Shiny today in 2023, this is

00:01:41.919 --> 00:01:44.559
not a delightful experience.

00:01:44.559 --> 00:01:51.440
Unfortunately, a lot of people are still encountering the same sort of hello world code that was

00:01:51.440 --> 00:02:00.480
designed and created for a world in 2013, and it's just something that we haven't put

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:06.120
on the top of our priority list for kind of bringing this first getting started experience

00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:11.160
into the next generation of Shiny UI.

00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:16.440
And also, to be fair, it's not necessarily fair to zero in on the hello world experience

00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:22.960
of Shiny, because really the thing that makes Shiny so awesome and makes it stand out from

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:30.880
maybe other competitors is the really awesome set, the really rich ecosystem of extensions

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:36.520
that all of you have built around Shiny.

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:43.279
But the thing about this extension ecosystem and Shiny itself is it turns out that a lot

00:02:43.279 --> 00:02:50.360
of these tools end up leaning on this popular UI framework called Bootstrap, and they tend

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:58.240
to lean on this UI framework to take care of some of the details behind styling and

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:05.679
design decisions, and in some cases, functionality for some of these UI components.

00:03:05.679 --> 00:03:10.759
And if you didn't know, even things like technically outside of the Shiny ecosystem, like maybe

00:03:10.759 --> 00:03:19.000
R Markdown or Quarto or Packagedown or Bookdown, these projects as well, chances are if you're

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:24.919
creating a website through an R package, chances are it's probably using Bootstrap at some

00:03:24.919 --> 00:03:30.839
level to provide styling and functionality.

00:03:30.839 --> 00:03:35.679
And unfortunately, if Shiny were just to upgrade Bootstrap by default, we would force a lot

00:03:35.679 --> 00:03:41.080
of people into doing a lot of work to update their projects so that they're not left in

00:03:41.080 --> 00:03:43.559
a broken state.

00:03:43.559 --> 00:03:50.440
And even if you're not a maintainer of one of these projects, even if you just created

00:03:50.440 --> 00:03:56.800
a sophisticated Shiny application and you've written some JavaScript or CSS, if we were

00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:00.440
to upgrade Bootstrap, that would potentially break some of the code that you've written

00:04:00.440 --> 00:04:04.880
and cause you a lot of work to update.

00:04:04.880 --> 00:04:10.479
Now one good example of this is Shiny Dashboard, which not only depends on Bootstrap, but also

00:04:10.479 --> 00:04:18.920
depends on additional dashboarding dependencies that also build on Bootstrap and haven't done

00:04:18.920 --> 00:04:25.640
really a great job in recent years of keeping up to date with Bootstrap and making sure

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:30.440
that they're not making breaking changes to things that would break an update to Shiny

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:33.640
Dashboard, for example.

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:42.519
So lately we've been working towards building out a framework that can kind of replace Shiny

00:04:42.519 --> 00:04:50.519
Dashboard and improve upon it, and making that available through the bslibr package.

00:04:50.519 --> 00:04:57.119
And even if you haven't already heard of bslib, chances are you've already used it, because

00:04:57.119 --> 00:05:03.920
it's now a dependency of Shiny and R Markdown and has kind of become a centralized home

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:10.179
for Bootstrap assets and logic that we've written that builds on top of Bootstrap, kind

00:05:10.179 --> 00:05:16.440
of like a central repository for these things to live and be shared across projects.

00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:22.679
And you may have already used bslib more directly to upgrade your project to a modern version

00:05:22.679 --> 00:05:27.640
of Bootstrap, which, among other things, gives you access to really rich, powerful

00:05:27.640 --> 00:05:31.140
theming tools.

00:05:31.140 --> 00:05:37.299
But more recently we've been broadening the scope of how we think about bslib to include

00:05:37.299 --> 00:05:44.600
a library of UI components that are primarily focused on dashboarding, but we also are creating

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:51.000
these with in mind that you might want to be able to use these components not only in

00:05:51.000 --> 00:06:01.040
a dashboard, but maybe in a Korto document or a Markdown or some other non-Shiny context.

00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:06.160
So that said, with these components, you can make a great-looking Shiny Dashboard like

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:08.279
this one.

00:06:08.279 --> 00:06:12.720
And these components should feel familiar, both in terms of how you express them and

00:06:12.720 --> 00:06:18.079
how you interact with them, but are going to look a lot more modern and better by default,

00:06:18.079 --> 00:06:23.000
but also allow you to go much deeper with styling and their functionality.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:28.959
So let me give you a high-level overview of how I created this dashboard.

00:06:28.959 --> 00:06:33.839
First of all, at the top here I have a nav bar at the very top of the page where I have

00:06:33.839 --> 00:06:39.019
a title and a logo on the left-hand side, but on the right-hand side I have some navigation

00:06:39.019 --> 00:06:43.320
links that allow me to navigate to different pages in this dashboard.

00:06:43.320 --> 00:06:47.399
Now we're just going to focus basically on this first page of this dashboard for this

00:06:47.399 --> 00:06:54.000
talk, but to initialize this UI I can use this page nav bar function from BS Lib and

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:59.679
give it multiple page definitions to get this top-level nav bar with navigation to the different

00:06:59.679 --> 00:07:02.480
pages.

00:07:02.480 --> 00:07:07.959
And page nav bar comes with a sidebar argument where I can just start supplying UI elements

00:07:08.119 --> 00:07:14.200
to this sidebar, and I get this nice page-level sidebar that's left-aligned with the main

00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:17.320
content area.

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:21.920
And in my case here for this dashboard, I have a lot of controls, so I'm going to group

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:24.959
them together with an accordion component.

00:07:24.959 --> 00:07:29.640
And this accordion component can be used outside of a sidebar, it can be used inside of a sidebar,

00:07:29.640 --> 00:07:35.399
and we have special awareness of that situation to make it look nice and render flush in the

00:07:35.399 --> 00:07:37.279
sidebar.

00:07:37.279 --> 00:07:44.559
But this is going to help me keep visual proximity amongst related controls, and also help users

00:07:44.559 --> 00:07:50.519
kind of scan sets of related controls in a way that's a lot better than just dumping

00:07:50.519 --> 00:07:56.720
dozens of input controls in a sidebar, but give it some nice organization and allow you

00:07:56.720 --> 00:07:59.119
to scan a little bit better.

00:07:59.119 --> 00:08:06.359
So here by default I'm showing you basically input controls for searching for a flight

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:13.399
path or flight carriers, but we could also be searching by controls related to flight

00:08:13.399 --> 00:08:16.079
time and weather.

00:08:16.079 --> 00:08:21.239
So let me go ahead and open up this section called flight time, which has some input controls

00:08:21.239 --> 00:08:27.600
inside of it, and then this gives me some histograms, histogram sliders that allow me

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:34.599
to filter by departure time and arrival time.

00:08:34.840 --> 00:08:40.039
All right, so moving on to the main content area of this dashboard, in this first row

00:08:40.039 --> 00:08:47.039
I have three different value boxes that's showing me the total number of flights and

00:08:47.559 --> 00:08:52.479
the average departure delay and the average arrival delay.

00:08:52.479 --> 00:08:56.880
And here to lay out these value boxes in this single row with basically like three different

00:08:56.880 --> 00:09:03.880
columns, I can give these value boxes to this layout columns mechanism, which will by default

00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:10.640
kind of guess that I want to place all three of these in one row in three different columns

00:09:10.640 --> 00:09:13.760
with their widths divided equally.

00:09:13.760 --> 00:09:18.280
But of course you can go a lot deeper with this with doing like non-equal width columns

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:25.000
and even different widths at different breakpoints of device size.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:30.320
And here also I've just put icons into these value boxes, but as we'll see later we can

00:09:30.320 --> 00:09:35.719
also kind of customize what we put into this showcase area is what we call it.

00:09:35.719 --> 00:09:39.640
All right, in the next row I have two cards.

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:44.659
On the left here I'm displaying flight paths, and on the right-hand side I'm showing the

00:09:44.659 --> 00:09:47.919
average delay by carrier.

00:09:47.919 --> 00:09:54.919
Again I'm going to use layout columns to give me this kind of equal width column layout,

00:09:55.119 --> 00:10:01.239
and then supply it to different cards with Plotly outputs.

00:10:01.239 --> 00:10:06.799
So Plotly is providing the visualization itself, but the layout for the cards and the cards

00:10:06.799 --> 00:10:11.000
themselves are provided via the BSLib package.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:18.200
All right, and as it turns out, any card can gain the ability to expand to a full screen

00:10:18.200 --> 00:10:21.919
view by setting this full screen equal to true.

00:10:21.919 --> 00:10:25.719
It allows a user to come in and when they hover on this card they'll see a little icon

00:10:25.719 --> 00:10:29.760
to expand this card to a full screen view.

00:10:29.760 --> 00:10:33.479
So let's go ahead and expand this card to full screen.

00:10:33.479 --> 00:10:38.559
And this gives me a much better, closer look at these flight paths, the interactive version

00:10:38.559 --> 00:10:43.640
I could like further zoom in on this globe and turn it around and stuff like that.

00:10:43.640 --> 00:10:47.520
But I want to focus on the BSLib aspect of this.

00:10:47.679 --> 00:10:52.599
Notice I have a title here at the top of the card and right aligned next to that I have

00:10:52.599 --> 00:10:55.479
this informational icon.

00:10:55.479 --> 00:10:59.799
That somebody could come in and hover on this icon and get more information about what's

00:10:59.799 --> 00:11:05.039
inside this visualization.

00:11:05.039 --> 00:11:10.320
And to implement this I'm using BSLib's tooltip, which is a pretty general utility that allows

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:16.119
you to attach a tooltip to any UI element on any page.

00:11:16.119 --> 00:11:21.299
But here I'm using it to attach a tooltip to an icon, which in most cases you should

00:11:21.299 --> 00:11:25.280
probably be attaching tooltips to icons.

00:11:25.280 --> 00:11:28.799
And then also placing it inside of the card header.

00:11:28.799 --> 00:11:31.559
All right.

00:11:31.559 --> 00:11:39.119
So let's go back to our dashboard and let's zero in on the average delay by carrier.

00:11:39.119 --> 00:11:43.760
So I have a pretty similar setup here in terms of the BSLib components where I have a card

00:11:43.760 --> 00:11:45.320
and a card title.

00:11:45.320 --> 00:11:51.039
I also have an icon here up right aligned in the card header.

00:11:51.039 --> 00:11:57.760
But this icon, instead of a tooltip being attached to it, I'm going to attach a popover.

00:11:57.760 --> 00:12:04.159
Which conceptually popovers are quite similar to tooltips, but are going to allow you to

00:12:04.159 --> 00:12:10.239
actually interact with the stuff that goes inside of the tooltip.

00:12:10.239 --> 00:12:15.200
So if a user came in and clicked on this icon, they're going to get a popover that looks

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:16.840
like this.

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:21.880
And for this situation, I've decided to put in a couple input controls that allow me to

00:12:21.880 --> 00:12:29.359
kind of tweak parameters behind this particular visualization.

00:12:29.359 --> 00:12:36.960
So in this case, I've put a select input for people to customize what category that I'm

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:40.559
going to average over to look at the average delay.

00:12:40.559 --> 00:12:43.599
So I could switch from carrier to month.

00:12:43.599 --> 00:12:47.679
And now I get this bar chart by month instead of by carrier, and gives me a better idea

00:12:47.679 --> 00:12:51.679
of what time of the year to be flying.

00:12:51.679 --> 00:12:59.119
All right, so let's go back to the dashboard, and now let's zero in on the card on the bottom.

00:12:59.119 --> 00:13:04.880
All right, this is going to give me a better look and a closer look at the distribution

00:13:04.880 --> 00:13:09.000
of delay times, which is right skewed.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:14.960
But I want to focus in on, again, kind of the upper right-hand portion of this card,

00:13:14.960 --> 00:13:20.359
and highlight the fact that I actually have navigation links here, similar to how the

00:13:20.359 --> 00:13:24.919
navigation looks at the very top of the page.

00:13:24.919 --> 00:13:29.039
So you're going to create this in a pretty similar fashion to how you would create the

00:13:29.039 --> 00:13:34.320
page-level navigation, but this allows you to basically construct different views for

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:39.200
your card using navigation links at the top.

00:13:39.200 --> 00:13:44.880
So if you look at the interactive version of this, you'll get a different view of delay

00:13:44.880 --> 00:13:47.039
times over time.

00:13:47.039 --> 00:13:51.400
But for sake of this presentation, I'm going to skip over that view.

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:56.679
And I'm going to highlight this other icon in the upper right-hand portion of this card,

00:13:56.679 --> 00:14:04.119
which indicates that we have a right-positioned sidebar that's closed by default.

00:14:04.119 --> 00:14:10.080
So this is going to give me kind of a nice alternative to popovers, where I can use it

00:14:10.080 --> 00:14:16.039
in a similar way where I can provide essentially like a drawer of additional input controls

00:14:16.039 --> 00:14:21.919
that are particular to this visualization that allow me to customize, again, sort of

00:14:21.919 --> 00:14:26.359
parameters that are specific to what's inside of this card.

00:14:26.359 --> 00:14:31.479
So it kind of provides like a nice way for you to scope your controls to subregions of

00:14:31.479 --> 00:14:37.799
the page versus having just everything dumped into a page-level sidebar.

00:14:37.799 --> 00:14:43.760
So in this case, I could choose to split up this distribution by weekday.

00:14:43.760 --> 00:14:48.919
And then this isn't going to tell me a whole lot, but it kind of just shows a pretty stacked

00:14:48.919 --> 00:14:54.960
histogram where this distribution is now broken up by the day of the week.

00:14:54.960 --> 00:14:57.359
All right.

00:14:57.359 --> 00:15:02.400
So again, going back to our dashboard, there's one last component that I'd like to highlight

00:15:02.400 --> 00:15:10.119
here, which is this input dark mode, which essentially gives the user ability to toggle

00:15:10.119 --> 00:15:13.359
dark mode in the dashboard.

00:15:13.359 --> 00:15:15.919
So let me put that back inside of the nav bar.

00:15:15.919 --> 00:15:20.239
This is kind of like a standalone component that you could put anywhere on the page, but

00:15:20.239 --> 00:15:23.919
probably just put it inside of the nav bar at the top.

00:15:23.919 --> 00:15:26.200
That's where people would expect it to be.

00:15:26.200 --> 00:15:33.400
And when you click on this toggle, then that will essentially change bootstrap styling

00:15:33.400 --> 00:15:39.640
defaults to be based on dark mode instead of light mode.

00:15:39.640 --> 00:15:43.559
So this is a really nice option for putting some of the theming control in the hands of

00:15:43.559 --> 00:15:45.359
the user.

00:15:45.359 --> 00:15:52.440
But also remember with BSLib that we have a ton of control over styling defaults available

00:15:52.440 --> 00:15:56.440
to us inside of our R code.

00:15:56.440 --> 00:16:03.380
So say I wanted to change up the primary color, bring in a slightly different font, and maybe

00:16:03.380 --> 00:16:08.520
bring in some different background colors for the value boxes.

00:16:08.520 --> 00:16:14.200
I could, with a fairly small amount of code, update all of those things to have it look

00:16:14.200 --> 00:16:16.679
like this.

00:16:16.679 --> 00:16:22.719
And a fair amount of that heavy lifting is going to be done through the BS theme function

00:16:22.719 --> 00:16:31.640
from BSLib, which gives you access to like hundreds of different styling or theming defaults

00:16:31.640 --> 00:16:34.400
provided by bootstrap.

00:16:34.400 --> 00:16:42.239
So I can do a lot just by setting the primary color to a purple, bring in some Google fonts

00:16:42.840 --> 00:16:48.119
Using this font Google does a lot of work for you in terms of automatically importing

00:16:48.119 --> 00:16:56.400
font files, downloading them if need be, and actually caching them for future runs.

00:16:56.400 --> 00:17:01.400
So there's a lot you can do with customizing main colors and fonts with this BS theme.

00:17:01.400 --> 00:17:10.319
One thing you need to remember is to give this theme object to the page constructor.

00:17:10.319 --> 00:17:14.560
And now for a component like value box, we actually give you kind of theming options

00:17:14.560 --> 00:17:20.400
that are specific to that component, which allows you to like, you know, maybe have one

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:24.719
value box that's styled a little bit differently from another value box.

00:17:24.719 --> 00:17:30.839
But in this case, I'm using this gradient background feature to make all three of these

00:17:30.839 --> 00:17:37.099
value boxes have like this nice gradient background.

00:17:37.099 --> 00:17:43.739
Another nice thing about working in BSLib that you might not notice right away is the

00:17:43.739 --> 00:17:48.979
fact that by default, you're not going to have this awkward empty space at the bottom

00:17:48.979 --> 00:17:52.500
of your main content region.

00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:58.020
And this is because BSLib gives you a filling layout by default, meaning that on larger

00:17:58.020 --> 00:18:04.780
displays, outputs will kind of grow to take up any available space in the window.

00:18:04.780 --> 00:18:10.500
And then as you make the window smaller, those outputs will shrink to basically evenly

00:18:10.500 --> 00:18:14.300
divide up the available space.

00:18:14.300 --> 00:18:15.420
Like this.

00:18:15.420 --> 00:18:19.300
But of course, it also gives you options for opting out of this filling layout feature

00:18:19.300 --> 00:18:21.260
if you need to.

00:18:21.260 --> 00:18:23.099
Right?

00:18:23.099 --> 00:18:28.260
So if you'd like to play with the interactive version of this app, feel free to screenshot

00:18:28.260 --> 00:18:29.260
this QR code.

00:18:29.260 --> 00:18:35.219
I'll give you a link to this bit.ly forward slash BSLib flights.

00:18:35.219 --> 00:18:37.939
If you want, you can search for your flight home.

00:18:37.939 --> 00:18:39.979
This app has...

00:18:39.979 --> 00:18:43.780
These are all flights leaving from Chicago in 2022.

00:18:43.780 --> 00:18:49.219
Should give you an idea of what kind of delay you should be expecting.

00:18:49.219 --> 00:18:53.739
And also, if you view it on your phone, it'll give you a good sense of how these layouts

00:18:54.060 --> 00:18:59.739
work pretty well and intelligently on mobile devices as well.

00:18:59.739 --> 00:19:05.739
But maybe all don't visit it at once, because maybe I don't know.

00:19:05.739 --> 00:19:07.579
All right.

00:19:07.579 --> 00:19:11.660
So to bring everything together, this is just a screen recording of me kind of searching

00:19:11.660 --> 00:19:12.739
for different flight paths.

00:19:12.739 --> 00:19:16.060
I have 30 seconds left.

00:19:16.060 --> 00:19:20.140
I want to step back for just a second and mention there's kind of three common themes

00:19:20.140 --> 00:19:23.859
that work well in information-rich applications.

00:19:23.859 --> 00:19:29.420
If you keep in mind overview first, like don't overwhelm your user, give them something high

00:19:29.420 --> 00:19:34.300
level and useful to take away, then give them tools for zooming and filtering, drilling

00:19:34.300 --> 00:19:38.420
down into stuff they're interested in, and then getting details on demand through tool

00:19:38.420 --> 00:19:40.380
tips and popovers.

00:19:40.380 --> 00:19:45.060
I like this kind of example that kind of does all three at once, where I have a bunch of

00:19:45.060 --> 00:19:47.579
value boxes with a spark line inside of them.

00:19:47.579 --> 00:19:50.699
And I can make it full screen and get details.

00:19:50.699 --> 00:19:51.699
Thank you very much.

00:19:51.699 --> 00:19:52.699
Thank you.

00:19:52.699 --> 00:19:52.699


